  'Meeting Notes: Ponce Bank & MiD: Weekly Sync',
  '## **Branding and Design Updates**

The team decided to revert to the **old font, P22 Mackinaw, for headlines** while considering a new sub-font with full weight and style variations (09:22).

- **Jane approved the new recommended sub-font visually**, pending confirmation of available weights and italics to match Proxima Nova''s flexibility (09:53).
- **Sales sheets will switch to landscape format with a product tree** to help sales reps identify upsell opportunities and related products more easily (10:27).
- **Trifold brochure edits are underway**, aligning with feedback and improving clarity (10:27).
- **Homepage redesign is in progress**, integrating existing content and new material provided by Victor, aiming for a fresh user experience (10:53).
- **Social media templates exist in Canva and are being updated with new fonts** before transferring to Jane’s account for quick, frequent brand announcement posts (11:10).
- Christina stressed the need to differentiate between reusable templates and unique assets for various social media use cases to avoid creative constraints (12:50).
- A meeting will be set to review brand assets with Jane’s team and coordinate template creation, involving Rebecca for workflow management (13:30).
- **Logo issues surfaced with incorrect white knockout versions**, causing delays; Jane will locate the correct EPS file for proper conversion and use across designs (16:16).
- The team is exploring how to better use compliance space on mailers, considering quadrant layouts and color differentiation inspired by competitors like Chase and TD for clearer communication (21:30).
- Colin will research additional print vendors and mail houses to find a better fit for mailing requirements and HubSpot API integration for automation (23:27).

## **Project Management and Meeting Structure**

The team agreed to separate meetings into two focused weekly sessions: one for **website and operational project management** and another for **creative and brand management led by Jane** (14:20).

- Victor and Rebecca will coordinate scheduling and take lead on project management calls, while Christina and Jane will act as strategic partners for the website and creative sides, respectively (15:20).
- This structure aims to avoid short, scattered discussions and improve focus, allowing 30 minutes per topic for better progress tracking (14:50).
- Colin confirmed ongoing font updates and brand guideline revisions across all deliverables, with continued integration of social, email, and print elements into HubSpot workflows (32:00).

## **Google Ads Account Recovery and Campaign Control**

Christina reported being locked out of the **Google Ads account due to outdated recovery info linked to a former employee’s phone**, which escalated the lockout period from 5 to **30 days, expiring on the meeting day** (17:19).

- Colin acknowledged the issue as common with multiple concurrent logins and committed to working with Google support to regain access (18:19).
- The team requested a full audit of ad accounts to confirm ownership and access, as rogue campaigns linked to mortgage lending rates could impact spend and compliance (18:52).
- Documentation such as tax forms may be needed for verification; Colin will coordinate with Christina and keep her updated on progress (19:30).

## **Website, Data Integration, and Timeline Confidence**

Christina expressed concern about the project''s timeline, noting that **they are less than four months from the January go-live date** and emphasized the need for a clear consensus on deadlines with executive stakeholders (25:31).

- Colin reassured that the internal team can build HubSpot workflows quickly once data properties are ready but stressed dependency on the Ponte team for data preparation and system access (25:48).
- A contingency plan was discussed: if key resources like Gabe or Ashley become unavailable, Colin’s team can step in, provided they receive MuleSoft and system access to avoid delays (27:29).
- The website redesign is progressing independently of data integration, allowing a scalable launch with placeholders for data-dependent features to avoid hold-ups (29:51).
- Christina recommended visually **color-coding the timeline by component**—website, social/digital, and data—to clarify dependencies and allow staggered go-lives that minimize financial risk (30:29).
- Colin confirmed prior internal use of color codes and agreed to reintroduce them for clearer milestone tracking (31:45).

## **Social Media Management and Platform Transition**

The team is moving to manage **social posting through HubSpot**, aiming to phase out Sprout Social by **February 1st** for streamlined operations (32:31).

- Jane and Christina will manage the marketing@Ponce email login, sharing credentials with Rebecca, who will learn to operate social posting within HubSpot (33:18).
- Jane raised concerns about shared logins tied to phone numbers and recommended separate personal sign-ons to prevent future lockouts or security issues (34:24).
- Christina confirmed limited user licenses and that alerts will funnel to the shared marketing inbox, allowing team-wide visibility (34:40).
- The HubSpot mobile app offers social management features, though the team needs to evaluate its capability for swift comment moderation and real-time engagement (35:41).
- The team plans a 30-minute training session for Jane, Rebecca, and Colin to review HubSpot’s social tools and establish a clear content management and channel management strategy (36:10).
- Duplicate posts occurred due to simultaneous Instagram live settings; a review of platform settings and posting workflows is planned to avoid future overlaps (36:45).
- Colin rescheduled the social meeting to the following week to accommodate availability, indicating ongoing adjustment and learning as the platform is adopted (39:12).

## **Upcoming Deliverables and Stakeholder Engagement**

- Christina requested early visibility on website templates and sitemaps to provide timely feedback and reduce extensive redesigns later (37:30).
- Colin is updating the sitemap to include missing pages and hidden content, aiming for a full site refresh aligned with brand updates (37:50).
- The team will continue refining brand assets, social templates, and mailer options, prioritizing the integration of HubSpot workflows and external vendor selections (32:00, 23:27).
- Coordination between creative, data, and digital teams will be formalized through the new meeting structure to maintain momentum and clear communication on dependencies and deadlines (14:20).',
