 detailed competitor analysis, industry snapshots, and target account empathy maps to ground strategy decisions\n    - Roadmaps present high-level marketing strategy and ideal customer profiles; foundation folders document how campaigns are built and segmented by channels\n    - Execution folders segment materials by campaign type and industry, supporting easy retrieval within 30 seconds per Colin’s organizational rule\n    - Lists for outreach are to be consolidated into a master spreadsheet with tabs per campaign and industry to improve clarity and cleanup\n\n- Rachel Curtis confirmed podcast-related assets are fully organized by episode and month, with pending additions for recent episodes and AI-specific visual corrections (13:05)\n    - Colin committed to adding missing Instagram carousel assets and updating AI imagery flagged by Rachel for quality issues\n    - All design packages and playbooks, including infographics and social media formats, are stored centrally for quick team access\n\n- Paid media assets, including ad creatives and LinkedIn contact lists, are included in designated folders, with monthly receipts tracked for financial oversight (17:37)\n    - Contact lists used for paid campaigns will be synchronized with the master outreach spreadsheet to ensure consistency\n\n## **Subscription and Platform Management**\n\nThe team clarified ownership and billing responsibility for key podcast and marketing platforms to ensure seamless control and cost management (23:19).\n\n- On **Buzzsprout**, Colin confirmed Noada Consultants holds admin rights and billing ownership, with Rachel and Nancie discussing adding internal team members for continuity in emergencies (23:19)\n    - Rachel plans to coordinate with Racky to add team visibility and remove inactive users to maintain access control\n    - Colin will share login details securely via Teams chat\n\n- For **Heyreach**, the subscription is under client control with a monthly cost of **$79**, and billing can be transferred directly to the client credit card before the month-end cutoff to avoid overlap (25:27)\n    - Nancie highlighted the importance of completing this transfer promptly to maintain uninterrupted service\n    - Colin provided step-by-step guidance on accessing billing settings to update payment methods\n\n- The team agreed to monitor these platform transitions closely to prevent service gaps and maintain efficient operations\n\n## **Process Improvements and Next Steps**\n\nThe team emphasized simplifying file retrieval and campaign tracking to improve operational efficiency and decision-making clarity (10:04).\n\n- Colin will clean up and standardize naming conventions across all lists and campaign files to reduce search time and duplication (10:44)\n    - Nancie requested a master spreadsheet tabbed by campaign sequence: healthcare, attractions, heads of marketing, AI, plus a re-engagement tab for cross-cutting efforts\n    - This structure will support sequential review and help the team track progress and performance chronologically\n\n- The zip folder containing all campaign assets and analysis will be uploaded to Box, with contingency plans to break up the upload if the file size exceeds system limits (22:17)\n    - Rachel will coordinate the upload and alert Colin if the process becomes too time-consuming, to divide and conquer as needed\n\n- Colin will send the final AI campaign report, updated podcast episode files, and corrected AI visuals promptly to close outstanding content and quality gaps (14:00)\n    - He also confirmed his availability, noting he will be out on Wednesday and Thursday this week, so the team plans communication accordingly (28:02)\n\n- The group agreed to continue monitoring engagement and conversions closely to refine targeting and tactics as campaigns evolve, prioritizing data-driven decisions on industry focus and channel mix","outline":null,"keywords":["AI Campaign","Podcast Management","Campaign Analysis","Subscripti